  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Agree Option B, keep 形 section in Preface",
    "content": "**Agree with Option B, with one condition.**\n\nMoving the Key Terminological Decisions section to a glossary introduction is the right structural move — terminology belongs where readers will consult it during reading, not in a preface they read once before starting. The narrative arc the editor describes (title → author → structure → bilingual → 形 reinterpretation → experiential sequences → reading advice) is clean and philosophically coherent.\n\n**The condition:** The 形 reinterpretation section must remain in the Preface (which the editor already marks as non-negotiable — good). This is the one terminological decision that is not merely a translation choice but a framing decision that changes how the reader understands every subsequent use of \"the metaphysical\" in the collection. It belongs in the Preface because it is prerequisite context, not reference material.\n\nAgree with both smaller trims as well. The forward references to \"digestion\" and \"knowledge sub-category\" would indeed confuse a first-time reader who hasn't encountered those concepts yet."
  }
}
